    <item>
      <title>Introduction to R Language</title>
      <link>https://mauriciovancine.github.io/workshop/workshop-r-unesp-ecology-2021/</link>
      <pubDate>Wed, 10 Nov 2021 09:00:00 +0000</pubDate>
      <guid>https://mauriciovancine.github.io/workshop/workshop-r-unesp-ecology-2021/</guid>
      <description>
&lt;script src=&#34;https://mauriciovancine.github.io/workshop/workshop-r-unesp-ecology-2021/index_files/header-attrs/header-attrs.js&#34;&gt;&lt;/script&gt;


&lt;p&gt;The workshop will introduce you to the fundamentals of the R language and RStudio IDE for manipulating and visualizing data through the tidyverse. tidyverse is a set of packages and functions that share the same framework to help users create efficient and ‘organized’ code. Packages are focused mainly in data organization (reading, filtering, organizing, selecting and summarizing) and viewing of data. The following topics will be addressed: (1) presentation, (2) functioning of the R language, (3) object structure and manipulation, (4) tidyverse and (5) data visualization. At the end of the short course, that participants acquire introductory knowledge of the functioning of language, as well as in manipulation and visualization of tabular data.&lt;/p&gt;
</description>
    </item>
    
    <item>
      <title>Introduction to species distribution modeling using the R language</title>
      <link>https://mauriciovancine.github.io/workshop/workshop-sdm-moco-2021/</link>
      <pubDate>Sat, 25 Sep 2021 09:00:00 +0000</pubDate>
      <guid>https://mauriciovancine.github.io/workshop/workshop-sdm-moco-2021/</guid>
      <description>
&lt;script src=&#34;https://mauriciovancine.github.io/workshop/workshop-sdm-moco-2021/index_files/header-attrs/header-attrs.js&#34;&gt;&lt;/script&gt;


&lt;p&gt;The wide availability of data on biodiversity and environmental variables favor the use of spatial analysis, including the Species Distribution Modeling (SDM). In this workshop, I will offer a theoretical and practical introduction to the SDM technique using the R language. First, I will briefly present the main concepts of ecological niche theory (Grinnell, Elton and Hutchinson) and DEM theory (geographical space (G), space environmental (E) and Biotic-Abiotic-Movement diagram (BAM)). Following the theoretical part, I will present the main databases (occurrences and environmental variables), types of algorithms (BIOCLIM, Mahalanobis, Gower, GLM, GAM, Random Forest, SVM and MaxEnt), evaluation of models (ROC, AUC and TSS) , cut-off limits (thresholds) and model consensus (ensembles). The practical part will focus on the construction of models using the R language, where I will address: (1) introduction to the R language, (2) obtaining and selecting data on occurrences and environmental variables, (3) adjusting and predicting the models, (4) evaluation metrics, (5) model consensus (ensembles) and (6) map composition.&lt;/p&gt;
</description>
    </item>
    
